bib_record.title: Oxygen-16 induced fission of 209Bi at 89.5 MeV

free_txt: Studies on the oxygen-16 induced fission of 209Bi
have been carried out at particle energies of 89.5 MeV
using gamma ray spectrometry. The cross sections for
the production of fission products have been
determined. The yield distribution of fission
products was found to be symmetric and broad with
FWHM around 15 mass units and peak near mass 108.
Charge distribution studies in the oxygen-16 induced
fission of 209Bi has also been carried out at
particle energy of 89.5 MeV. Relative cumulative
yields of 92Sr, 97Zr, 99Mo, 101Mo, 112Pd and 117mCd
have been determined using gamma ray spectrometry.
Width of charge distribution has been found to be
broad. Total cross section in the oxygen-16 induced
reaction of 27Al at particle energy of 76.1 MeV been
carried out.
Resolution of 2.0 keV at 1332 keV.
The errors listed are the standard deviations
between the results from five different irradiations
and different gamma rays used for the same nuclide.
Samples were irradiated for a suitable
length of time so as to determine both the short and
long lived fission products.
In each irradiation the decay of the gamma ray
peak of the fission products were followed for
suitable length of time so as to have minimum error
due to counting statistics.
The dead time correction at the amplifier stage for
the count rate was carried out using reference peak of
1368 keV of 24Na.
The cumulative production cross section was determined
for most of the mass chains. In case of shielded nuclei
independent production cross section was determined.
In the case of 85mKr, 106mRh, 115Cd, 116m-In and 117mCd
only one isomeric state was studied which gives partial
cross section for the nuclide.
Targets of super pure 209Bi (0.837 mg/cm2 thick) were
prepared by vacuum evaporation on 7.6 mumeter super
pure aluminum foil.
In order to avoid the cross contamination of fission
products due to large activity of direct reaction
products, the 209Bi target was covered with a
0.76 mumeter super pure Al foil.
This will allow the fission products to pass and will
prevent the reaction products. The whole assembly was
put in a target holder and irradiated for a suitable
length of time with 96 MeV 16O particle beam of
~100 nA. The average incident 16O ion energy on the
Bi targets was 89.5 MeV, whereas the average energy on
the aluminum catcher foil was 76.1 MeV.
